    <title>Combined summary - Standardisation of an unstructured taproot annex</title>
    <updated>2023-06-18T12:21:44.673049+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2023-June/021772.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Taproot annex is a new feature introduced by Taproot that allows developers to include additional data in the SegWit witness of a transaction. However, discussions have arisen around standardization and its potential risks such as annex malleability vector. One solution suggested was to limit the annex usage to 126 bytes or require all inputs to commit to an annex to be relay-standard. It has been proposed to define any annex that begins with '0' as free-form without additional constraints, allowing developers to utilize the taproot annex immediately without waiting for a structured format.The email thread on the bitcoin-dev mailing list discusses various aspects of the Taproot annex, including its potential use cases and challenges associated with its adoption. The annex is believed to improve space efficiency and is useful for data storage uses that utilize OP_RETURN or inscriptions. One critical application of the annex is time-locked vaults, which can be safeguarded using pre-signed transactions signed using an ephemeral key and backed up on the blockchain using the annex. The taproot annex is currently a consensus valid but non-standard feature that can allow developers to include additional data in the SegWit witness of a transaction. There are conversations around standardizing it, and while a flexible Type-Length-Value (TLV) format is being considered, agreeing on an exact format may take time. In the meantime, a proposal has been made to define any annex that begins with '0' as free-form without additional constraints, allowing developers to utilize the taproot annex immediately without waiting for a structured format.The email exchange among various bitcoin developers discusses the potential adoption of a flexible Type-Length-Value (TLV) format for standardization, which may take significant time. The conversation mainly focuses on the adoption of a Taproot annex design to improve space efficiency and safeguard time-locked vaults using pre-signed transactions signed with ephemeral keys. However, there is a circular reference problem without an annex, making it less safe. Dave proposed a scriptpath solution and suggested other solutions for nearly the same safety without data being put on the chain. Antoine proposes adopting a simple approach to the Taproot annex to avoid a potentially long standardization process. He suggests a two-phase decentralized standardization process of the annex. Greg discusses the potential risks involved in crafting reliable payment systems for miners while enabling current users to make reasonable fee rate transactions. Joost proposes making annex usage opt-in to enable covenants through pre-signed transactions and asks whether it would still be necessary to restrict the annex to a maximum size.The email exchange highlights the importance of considering trade-offs when proposing changes and the potential solutions to address concerns about transaction-relay jamming griefing issues. Overall, the conversation emphasizes the potential benefits and challenges associated with the adoption of a taproot annex design for unstructured data use-cases and the importance of careful consideration of trade-offs and potential solutions. However, there are concerns around annex malleability and the potential for larger transactions causing longer mining times. It is suggested that Bitcoin may not be suited for certain types of applications and efforts should be focused on fixing annex malleability in a future soft fork.</summary>
